{
  "result": "At five thirty, the city still thinks it is asleep. Streetlights hum softly, diffusing halos onto damp asphalt while the last of the night rain slides into gutters. Delivery cyclists trace cautious arcs around puddles, their insulated bags blinking like little spacecraft signalling home. I stand by the bakery vent, letting sourdough breath warm my fingers, listening to the dough mixers grinding out a low, percussive heartbeat. Every dawn feels improvised, yet the ensemble rarely misses a cue.\n\nA bus exhales at the curb, releasing two nurses who share a yawn and an inside joke. They move with the choreography of habitual tenderness, arms brushing, steps synced. Behind them, a stray cat vaults a trash bin with aristocratic disdain, then pauses to accept my respect from a safe distance. The cat knows the economy of attention better than any influencer.\n\nSunlight takes its time, but eventually a thin blade slips between the towers, illuminating the graffiti mural that earns my applause daily. The artist repaints it each week, layering new colors over stubborn ghosts of slogans. Today, the wall declares, \u201cPractice astonishment responsibly.\u201d I take that as a reminder to aim my curiosity like a lamp, not a spotlight.\n\nNewsstands rattle open, spilling headlines that will dictate lunch arguments. A man in a suit rehearses a pitch beneath his breath, vowels sharpened like tools. Nearby, a florist unloads buckets of peonies, their petals shivering in the cool air, ready to bribe offices into gentleness. The city wakes with permissions granted.",
